metadata.last_judge_feedback:
{
  "correct": false,
  "explanation": "The model is very close to valid ProVerif, but there is a semantic type misuse: the FeatureFQ function is declared with argument type feature while it is used with an optionsbitmap argument, which will trigger a type error around the middle of the file (near the reported line 551). Fixing the type of FeatureFQ (and optionally its name) resolves this.",
  "issues": [
    "Line 86 (logical position): FeatureFQ is declared as fun FeatureFQ(feature): bool., but later called as FeatureFQ(featureFreq) where featureFreq: feature (OK) and also used in a guard that conceptually refers to the FeatureMap attribute, *not* to the frequency feature flag. This is more of a naming/semantics ambiguity than a syntax error.",
    "Line 421–430 (around the MoveToClosestFrequency branch, near the reported parser error): The guard uses eq_bool(FeatureFQ(featureFreq), true) but FeatureFQ was declared to take type feature. In the FSM JSON, FeatureFQ is clearly described as derived from FeatureMap (an attribute), not from a separate feature-typed state variable. The ProVerif model uses featureFreq: feature as the only feature-related variable, so using FeatureFQ(featureFreq) is a mismatch with the narrative semantics.",
    "Line 420–433 (same region): The semantics imply FeatureFQ should be a predicate on the FeatureMap/options bitmap, not on a separate feature type. As written, either the type of FeatureFQ is wrong or the type of featureFreq should be optionsbitmap / a dedicated FeatureMap type. This will surface as a type/semantic error when ProVerif typechecks, even though the immediate parser error message only points generically at a syntax error."
  ],
  "syntax_fixes": [
    {
      "line": 83,
      "error": "fun FeatureFQ(feature): bool.                                (* interpret FeatureMap bit for frequency *)",
      "fix": "fun FeatureFQ(optionsbitmap): bool.                         (* interpret FeatureMap/Options bitmap bit for frequency *)",
      "explanation": "In the rest of the model and in the FSM JSON, FeatureFQ is described as a boolean interpretation of a feature bit embedded in FeatureMap/Options-like bitmaps. The only feature-related runtime value carried in DeviceFSM is featureFreq, which is currently typed as feature but is treated semantically like a bitmap-derived flag. Making FeatureFQ take optionsbitmap (or renaming featureFreq’s type to optionsbitmap) aligns the declaration with its use in guards. This resolves the type inconsistency that ProVerif reports close to line 551."
    },
    {
      "line": 103,
      "error": "fun FeatureFQ(feature): bool.                                (* interpret FeatureMap bit for frequency *)",
      "fix": "(* Alternatively, if you really want a separate feature type, change the FSM parameter type: *)\n(* 1. Keep FeatureFQ as is: *)\nfun FeatureFQ(feature): bool.\n(* 2. Change DeviceFSM’s last parameter and all corresponding occurrences: *)\nlet DeviceFSM(...,\n              featureFreq: feature) =\n(* and ensure you never pass an optionsbitmap to FeatureFQ. *)",
      "explanation": "Alternative fix if you intend featureFreq to be an abstract feature flag of type feature. In that case, keep FeatureFQ(feature) but be sure you never call FeatureFQ with an optionsbitmap. Given your JSON semantics, the first fix (FeatureFQ: optionsbitmap) is usually the better match."
    },
    {
      "line": 244,
      "error": "else if band(eq_command(rcmd, cmd_MoveToClosestFrequency),\n                         eq_bool(FeatureFQ(featureFreq), true)) then",
      "fix": "else if band(eq_command(rcmd, cmd_MoveToClosestFrequency),\n                         eq_bool(FeatureFQ(featureFreq), true)) then",
      "explanation": "Once FeatureFQ’s argument type matches the type of featureFreq (either both feature or both optionsbitmap), this line is syntactically and semantically valid. No change to the guard itself is required beyond the corrected function type above."
    }
  ],
  "semantic_issues": [
    "FeatureFQ is documented in the JSON as a boolean interpretation of the Frequency feature bit in the FeatureMap attribute, but in the ProVerif model it is a function over a separate type feature, and the only variable of that type (featureFreq) is carried as a state parameter without any clear link to the FeatureMap attribute. This is more of a modeling mismatch than a pure syntax error, but it can lead to confusion in reasoning about the FrequencyConstraintRespect property.",
    "The FeatureMap attribute constant attr_FeatureMap is declared but not used anywhere in the process; instead, the availability of the frequency feature is modeled by featureFreq and FeatureFQ(featureFreq). For stronger traceability to the original specification, you may want to add events or guards that explicitly connect featureFreq to attr_FeatureMap (for instance via an AttributeChanged event or an initialization function)."
  ],
  "fsm_coverage": {
    "states_covered": [
      "st_IdleOff",
      "st_IdleOn",
      "st_LevelTransitionOff",
      "st_LevelTransitionOnBase",
      "st_LevelTransitionOnWithOnOff"
    ],
    "states_missing": [],
    "transitions_covered": 100,
    "transitions_missing": [
      "All externally visible FSM transitions are represented in abstracted form, but some distinctions (e.g., ExecuteIfOff-driven subcases, certain overlapping Move/Step behaviors while already in transition) are merged into shared if-branches. This is intentional abstraction rather than outright omission."
    ]
  }
}
